activist background because

00:27:36.060 --> 00:27:38.500 align:middle line:90%
of my mother and grandmother.

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:41.750 align:middle line:84%
So it just helped
me get involved

00:27:41.750 --> 00:27:43.530 align:middle line:90%
with activism in America.

00:27:43.530 --> 00:27:46.530 align:middle line:84%
So then I became president of
the Hunter College Feminists

00:27:46.530 --> 00:27:51.430 align:middle line:84%
Club, and we did lots
of fun activists things,

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:54.260 align:middle line:84%
including that I was
one of two students

00:27:54.260 --> 00:27:58.350 align:middle line:84%
to propose and help create the
CUNY-wide sexual assault policy

00:27:58.350 --> 00:27:59.740 align:middle line:90%
for half a million students.

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:00.440 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:01.480 align:middle line:90%
That's amazing.

00:28:01.480 --> 00:28:02.730 align:middle line:90%
She's incredible.

00:28:02.730 --> 00:28:05.490 align:middle line:84%
And Jerin has an amazing
voice, and a very articulate,

00:28:05.490 --> 00:28:07.690 align:middle line:90%
powerful, fierce, brave voice.

00:28:07.690 --> 00:28:09.820 align:middle line:10%
Last year, when we did
One Billion Rising,

00:28:09.820 --> 00:28:12.410 align:middle line:10%
we were looking at a lot of the
intersections around violence

00:28:12.410 --> 00:28:18.610 align:middle line:10%
against women, how it
impacts economic violence,

00:28:18.610 --> 00:28:21.600 align:middle line:10%
how racism, how Islamophobia.

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:26.224 align:middle line:84%
And she wrote a really
brilliant piece on Islamophobia.

00:28:26.224 --> 00:28:27.790 align:middle line:84%
And you should talk about
that, because I think

00:28:27.790 --> 00:28:29.610 align:middle line:84%
it's really important
to put that forward

00:28:29.610 --> 00:28:31.270 align:middle line:90%
so we keep thinking about it.

00:28:31.270 --> 00:28:32.260 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:28:32.260 --> 00:28:35.190 align:middle line:84%
So I think there's a
lot of Islamophobia

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:36.730 align:middle line:90%
in American and beyond.

00:28:36.730 --> 00:28:40.270 align:middle line:84%
And some of it, as a Muslim
woman, I understand why.

00:28:40.270 --> 00:28:42.910 align:middle line:84%
What happened in 9/11
and the terrorist attacks

00:28:42.910 --> 00:28:47.240 align:middle line:84%
that have happened since
then have shaken all of us

00:28:47.240 --> 00:28:47.960 align:middle line:90%
to the core.

00:28:47.960 --> 00:28:51.900 align:middle line:84%
And I can understand how it's
human nature to react in anger,

00:28:51.900 --> 00:28:55.130 align:middle line:84%
and make this one
race as the other,

00:28:55.130 --> 00:28:57.550 align:middle line:84%
because then maybe we
can protect ourselves.

00:28:57.550 --> 00:28:59.880 align:middle line:84%
But the truth is, there's
more than a billion

00:28:59.880 --> 00:29:01.170 align:middle line:90%
Muslims in the world.

00:29:01.170 --> 00:29:02.910 align:middle line:84%
And if each one of
them were a terrorist,

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:05.924 align:middle line:84%
we would be in a really
bad place right now.

00:29:05.924 --> 00:29:06.900 align:middle line:90%
Indeed.

00:29:06.900 --> 00:29:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And I think that also
translates into how

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:12.000 align:middle line:90%
women are viewed, Muslim women.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:16.860 align:middle line:84%
They're viewed as very
passive, and abused,

00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:19.230 align:middle line:84%
and religious, the
women that are treated

00:29:19.230 --> 00:29:21.380 align:middle line:90%
the worst of any culture.

00:29:21.380 --> 00:29:23.030 align:middle line:84%
And Eve knows this
better than anybody

00:29:23.030 --> 00:29:24.760 align:middle line:90%
else-- that's just not true.

00:29:24.760 --> 00:29:28.400 align:middle line:84%
In America, every
nine seconds, a woman

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:30.960 align:middle line:90%
is abused or sexually violated.

00:29:30.960 --> 00:29:32.390 align:middle line:90%
That's in America.

00:29:32.390 --> 00:29:35.250 align:middle line:84%
So to say one culture
is worse than another,

00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:37.470 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't help the
women of that culture.

00:29:37.470 --> 00:29:39.900 align:middle line:84%
It's really just others
that entire culture,

00:29:39.900 --> 00:29:42.100 align:middle line:84%
and it makes the women
from that culture

00:29:42.100 --> 00:29:46.400 align:middle line:84%
less likely to identify as
feminists, or to work with us.

00:29:46.400 --> 00:29:48.450 align:middle line:84%
Because they think, well,
they hate all of us.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:50.520 align:middle line:84%
Why would I wanna
work with them?

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:51.350 align:middle line:90%
I think that's so true.

00:29:51.350 --> 00:29:57.020 align:middle line:84%
And I was reading an
article today about Delhi.

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:00.100 align:middle line:84%
I was in Delhi at the
moment that Jyoti had been

00:30:00.100 --> 00:30:01.200 align:middle line:90%
murdered, like, right after.

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:02.470 align:middle line:84%
It was an incredible
time to be--

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:04.190 align:middle line:84%
Maybe tell people
what that story is.

00:30:04.190 --> 00:30:07.320 align:middle line:84%
Jyoti was a young woman who
got on the bus with her fiance,

00:30:07.320 --> 00:30:11.470 align:middle line:84%
and she ended up being horribly
gang-raped and murdered.

00:30:11.470 --> 00:30:13.910 align:middle line:84%
And the trial was
just this week,

00:30:13.910 --> 00:30:16.400 align:middle line:84%
and unfortunately, they've given
the death penalty to the people

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:18.570 align:middle line:90%
who raped and murdered her.

00:30:18.570 --> 00:30:20.140 align:middle line:84%
I'm very opposed to
the death penalty.

00:30:20.140 --> 00:30:23.630 align:middle line:84%
But I was in India at the moment
when the whole case exploded.

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:27.470 align:middle line:84%
And I was so moved to see
the response of Indians,

00:30:27.470 --> 00:30:28.520 align:middle line:90%
just the outpouring.

00:30:28.520 --> 00:30:30.850 align:middle line:84%
Every newspaper, every
magazine, every article

00:30:30.850 --> 00:30:32.360 align:middle line:84%
was about rape and
sexual violence.

00:30:32.360 --> 00:30:34.300 align:middle line:84%
To see an entire
country in uproar.

00:30:34.300 --> 00:30:35.760 align:middle line:84%
And so when I was
giving speeches,

00:30:35.760 --> 00:30:37.890 align:middle line:84%
I was like, this is the first
time I've ever seen this happen

00:30:37.890 --> 00:30:40.380 align:middle line:84%
in the history of the world
where violence against women

00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:42.100 align:middle line:84%
has been on the front
pages every single day.

00:30:42.100 --> 00:30:44.000 align:middle line:84%
I would love this to
happen in America.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:47.630 align:middle line:84%
And people got so angry at
me that I would actually

00:30:47.630 --> 00:30:49.410 align:middle line:90%
look to India for inspiration.

00:30:49.410 --> 00:30:50.890 align:middle line:84%
Heaven forbid America
would actually

00:30:50.890 --> 00:30:52.490 align:middle line:84%
look outside our
borders to be taught

00:30:52.490 --> 00:30:53.830 align:middle line:90%
something from other people.

00:30:53.830 --> 00:30:57.750 align:middle line:84%
But I think we end up demonizing
and otherizing groups so often.

00:30:57.750 --> 00:31:00.710 align:middle line:84%
People get categorized as
Muslim women, poor Muslim women,

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:04.040 align:middle line:84%
African women, poor--
when in fact, violence

00:31:04.040 --> 00:31:05.570 align:middle line:84%
against women and
patriarchy happens

00:31:05.570 --> 00:31:07.300 align:middle line:90%
to be universal and epidemic.

00:31:07.300 --> 00:31:08.996 align:middle line:84%
There isn't any culture
or country I've been to,

00:31:08.996 --> 00:31:10.050 align:middle line:90%
and I've been to many.

00:31:10.050 --> 00:31:10.880 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:31:10.880 --> 00:31:13.090 align:middle line:84%
I was gonna ask if you
see any, in that sense,

00:31:13.090 --> 00:31:15.000 align:middle line:84%
positive developments
over the last decade.

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.700 align:middle line:84%
Are there indicators, or
trends, or statistics?

00:31:17.700 --> 00:31:19.310 align:middle line:90%
I mean, is it a flatline?

00:31:19.310 --> 00:31:20.040 align:middle line:90%
Is it a positive?

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:22.160 align:middle line:90%
Is it a negative?

00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:23.930 align:middle line:84%
Is there any cultural
shift happening?

00:31:23.930 --> 00:31:25.430 align:middle line:90%
Well, here's the deal.

00:31:25.430 --> 00:31:28.610 align:middle line:84%
16 years ago, 30 years
ago, no one was talking

00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:29.620 align:middle line:90%
about violence against women.

00:31:29.620 --> 00:31:30.980 align:middle line:90%
It was just ordinary.

00:31:30.980 --> 00:31:32.270 align:middle line:90%
It was just what happened.

00:31:32.270 --> 00:31:33.570 align:middle line:84%
Well, Susan Brownmiller,
for instance.

00:31:33.570 --> 00:31:35.190 align:middle line:84%
Right, but that was
like 20 years ago.

00:31:35.190 --> 00:31:36.450 align:middle line:90%
More like 30, probably.

00:31:36.450 --> 00:31:37.410 align:middle line:90%
30.

00:31:37.410 --> 00:31:39.790 align:middle line:84%
Susan Brownmiller
was like, obviously,

00:31:39.790 --> 00:31:42.230 align:middle line:84%
the breakthrough book on
it. "Against Our Will"

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:43.650 align:middle line:90%
was the breakthrough book.

00:31:43.650 --> 00:31:46.120 align:middle line:84%
But that was the beginning
of consciousness.

00:31:46.120 --> 00:31:49.801 align:middle line:10%
But 30 years ago, even that,
it wasn't widely thought about,

00:31:49.801 --> 00:31:50.500 align:middle line:10%
or talked about.

00:31:50.500 --> 00:31:54.710 align:middle line:10%
So we're at a point now where
it is now front page news, where

00:31:54.710 --> 00:31:57.230 align:middle line:10%
you have a Todd Aiken last
year, who comes out and talks

00:31:57.230 --> 00:32:01.250 align:middle line:10%
about legitimate rape or
illegitimate rape, or imagined,

00:32:01.250 --> 00:32:04.305 align:middle line:10%
and there's an immediate and
amazing response to that.

00:32:04.305 --> 00:32:06.315 align:middle line:84%
That wasn't happening
30 years ago, you know?

00:32:06.315 --> 00:32:08.350 align:middle line:84%
We know that more women
are reporting rapes.

00:32:08.350 --> 00:32:10.480 align:middle line:84%
We know that more people
are documenting rapes.

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:12.530 align:middle line:84%
So it's hard to tell it
there's more rape happening

00:32:12.530 --> 00:32:14.370 align:middle line:84%
or if more people
are reporting it.

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:16.120 align:middle line:84%
What hasn't changed
is patriarchy.

00:32:16.120 --> 00:32:18.730 align:middle line:84%
We have not undone the
constructs of patriarchy.

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:21.120 align:middle line:84%
So I'm sure you have this
experience everywhere.

00:32:21.120 --> 00:32:22.880 align:middle line:90%
It just keeps repeating itself.

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:25.360 align:middle line:84%
And what are some of the
main avenues to do that?

00:32:25.360 --> 00:32:27.620 align:middle line:84%
I was thinking about the
microfinance campaigns

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:31.479 align:middle line:84%
that were seeking to
empower poor women.

00:32:31.479 --> 00:32:32.645 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, they
were the ones who

00:32:32.645 --> 00:32:34.000 align:middle line:90%
were getting most of the loans.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:37.580 align:middle line:84%
Do you see social trends or
ways that that empowerment

00:32:37.580 --> 00:32:39.380 align:middle line:90%
can accelerate?

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:42.184 align:middle line:90%
Do you wanna answer that?

00:32:42.184 --> 00:32:43.560 align:middle line:90%
You can go ahead.

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:45.440 align:middle line:84%
Well, I think
there's a lot of ways

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:46.750 align:middle line:90%
that we're empowering women.

00:32:46.750 --> 00:32:48.930 align:middle line:84%
One is through voice,
and by telling stories,

00:32:48.930 --> 00:32:50.550 align:middle line:84%
and by trusting
their own experience,

00:32:50.550 --> 00:32:51.890 align:middle line:90%
and not cutting off their voice.

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:53.230 align:middle line:84%
Someone earlier
was talking to me

00:32:53.230 --> 00:32:55.360 align:middle line:84%
about the fact that all their
lives they felt constricted.

00:32:55.360 --> 00:32:57.620 align:middle line:84%
They had no voice,
and what they felt,

00:32:57.620 --> 00:32:59.880 align:middle line:84%
and what they saw didn't matter,
and they were terrified to put

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:00.770 align:middle line:90%
it into the world.

00:33:00.770 --> 00:33:02.330 align:middle line:84%
I think that's
definitely changing.

00:33:02.330 --> 00:33:04.500 align:middle line:84%
I think we see many more artists
coming forward, many more

00:33:04.500 --> 00:33:06.110 align:middle line:90%
women in positions of power.

00:33:06.110 --> 00:33:11.640 align:middle line:84%
And I think the internet has
really democratized opinions.

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:14.640 align:middle line:84%
And women are having lots
of opinions on the internet.

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:18.260 align:middle line:84%
I think also the more we look
at programs where women are

00:33:18.260 --> 00:33:22.420 align:middle line:84%
empowered economically, where
we're looking at just the whole

00:33:22.420 --> 00:33:26.600 align:middle line:84%
the military-industrial system
and how that is creating

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:29.110 align:middle line:84%
a culture of violence
everywhere in the world,

00:33:29.110 --> 00:33:32.560 align:middle line:84%
I think those are incredibly
important factors.

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:34.880 align:middle line:84%
And I think building
communities and movements

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:38.120 align:middle line:84%
where women do not feel alone--
one of the things about One

00:33:38.120 --> 00:33:41.980 align:middle line:84%
Billion Rising is because
there was a world movement,

00:33:41.980 --> 00:33:45.370 align:middle line:84%
women in Mogadishu could rise,
because they were protected

00:33:45.370 --> 00:33:47.100 align:middle line:90%
by the global cone, right?

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:49.080 align:middle line:90%
Women in Bangladesh could rise.

00:33:49.080 --> 00:33:52.640 align:middle line:84%
Women in Alabama could rise,
which is just as risky there.

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:55.210 align:middle line:84%
And I think if we build
global communities,

00:33:55.210 --> 00:33:58.110 align:middle line:84%
women feel safe within
those communities,

00:33:58.110 --> 00:33:59.810 align:middle line:84%
because they're connected
to a bigger story.

00:33:59.810 --> 00:34:01.830 align:middle line:84%
And it's not just
their terrible culture.

00:34:01.830 --> 00:34:04.650 align:middle line:84%
It actually is
the world culture.

00:34:04.650 --> 00:34:07.330 align:middle line:84%
I was curious also-- I mean,
I was thinking about how,

00:34:07.330 --> 00:34:09.550 align:middle line:84%
yes, in the US,
maybe in Europe also,

00:34:09.550 --> 00:34:14.330 align:middle line:84%
there's a negative animus
around Islamic civilization,

00:34:14.330 --> 00:34:15.030 align:middle line:90%
Muslim culture.

00:34:15.030 --> 00:34:16.920 align:middle line:84%
That's probably
very unfortunate.

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:18.790 align:middle line:84%
And I would say that
one aspect of that

00:34:18.790 --> 00:34:21.429 align:middle line:84%
is the sense that
in Islamic cultures,

00:34:21.429 --> 00:34:23.580 align:middle line:90%
women have less opportunity to--

00:34:23.580 --> 00:34:24.741 align:middle line:84%
That's actually
not true at all.

00:34:24.741 --> 00:34:26.860 align:middle line:84%
OK.
Tell me about that.

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:29.469 align:middle line:10%
Islam, when it came
around, gave women rights,

00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:32.400 align:middle line:10%
like the right to
divorce, own property,

00:34:32.400 --> 00:34:35.010 align:middle line:10%
and do other things that
took Western nations

00:34:35.010 --> 00:34:37.760 align:middle line:10%
centuries to get to that point.

00:34:37.760 --> 00:34:41.860 align:middle line:84%
In the Quran, it gives
women so many rights.

00:34:41.860 --> 00:34:44.690 align:middle line:84%
It's patriarchy that has
taken that, and twisted it,

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:46.080 align:middle line:90%
and said--

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:48.260 align:middle line:84%
What are the rights that
it gives them, for example?

00:34:48.260 --> 00:34:51.780 align:middle line:84%
For example, in Afghanistan,
you know, Malala was shot,

00:34:51.780 --> 00:34:55.150 align:middle line:84%
because she was trying
to educate young girls.

00:34:55.150 --> 00:35:00.650 align:middle line:84%
In Islam, education and
learning is the same as prayer.

00:35:00.650 --> 00:35:04.540 align:middle line:84%
So these people who are
doing this violence,

00:35:04.540 --> 00:35:08.210 align:middle line:84%
not only are they bad
patriarchs, they're actually

00:35:08.210 --> 00:35:11.300 align:middle line:84%
very un-Islamic, because they're
trying to stop these women

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:14.290 align:middle line:90%
from conducting prayer.

00:35:14.290 --> 00:35:16.520 align:middle line:84%
From your perspective, does it
makes sense, though, to refer

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:17.760 align:middle line:90%
always back to the Quran?

00:35:17.760 --> 00:35:20.120 align:middle line:84%
Or in a way, I mean,
does an Islamic culture

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:23.380 align:middle line:84%
have to develop to where that's
a reference point, but not

00:35:23.380 --> 00:35:24.820 align:middle line:90%
the reference point in a way?

00:35:24.820 --> 00:35:26.280 align:middle line:84%
I think it has
to be individual.

00:35:26.280 --> 00:35:29.720 align:middle line:84%
You know, I'm lucky where
I come from a family where

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:30.810 align:middle line:90%
religion wasn't forced on me.

00:35:30.810 --> 00:35:32.940 align:middle line:90%
It was something I chose.

00:35:32.940 --> 00:35:36.170 align:middle line:84%
I think I chose to be
Muslim, because I found

00:35:36.170 --> 00:35:38.030 align:middle line:90%
it was so feminist, the Quran.

00:35:38.030 --> 00:35:39.340 align:middle line:90%
It was so empowering for me.

00:35:39.340 --> 00:35:40.525 align:middle line:90%
I've never heard that before.

00:35:40.525 --> 00:35:42.670 align:middle line:90%
It is so incredibly empowering.

00:35:42.670 --> 00:35:45.030 align:middle line:84%
All the rights that are
given to me by the Quran

00:35:45.030 --> 00:35:48.570 align:middle line:84%
are more than the American
government gives me.

00:35:48.570 --> 00:35:49.310 align:middle line:90%
Tell me more.

00:35:49.310 --> 00:35:51.230 align:middle line:84%
For example, there's
so many things

00:35:51.230 --> 00:35:53.830 align:middle line:84%
that are cultural
that are talked

00:35:53.830 --> 00:35:56.090 align:middle line:90%
about as if they're Islamic.

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:58.930 align:middle line:84%
For example, female
genital mutilation,

00:35:58.930 --> 00:36:01.020 align:middle line:84%
nowhere to be found
in the religion,

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:02.875 align:middle line:84%
but there are places
in Africa where--

00:36:02.875 --> 00:36:04.390 align:middle line:84%
But I was curious
more about the positive

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:07.070 align:middle line:90%
rights that you feel are--

00:36:07.070 --> 00:36:09.950 align:middle line:84%
Absolutely, for example,
in Islam, every penny

00:36:09.950 --> 00:36:13.160 align:middle line:84%
a woman who earns
belongs to her.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:15.080 align:middle line:84%
Nobody else has
any right to that.

00:36:15.080 --> 00:36:18.010 align:middle line:84%
I choose to do whatever
I with my money.

00:36:18.010 --> 00:36:21.460 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, that's not reality
in a lot of Muslim cultures

00:36:21.460 --> 00:36:23.270 align:middle line:84%
because of patriarchy.
-Mhm.

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:28.260 align:middle line:84%
So from your perspective, how do
you spread this understanding,

00:36:28.260 --> 00:36:29.910 align:middle line:84%
or make it more
generally understood?

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:31.556 align:middle line:84%
I think it's about
education, but I

00:36:31.556 --> 00:36:36.920 align:middle line:84%
think it's also about what Eve
did with me, this little girl

00:36:36.920 --> 00:36:38.720 align:middle line:84%
from New York, giving
her voice in One

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:42.310 align:middle line:84%
Billion Rising, to allow
Muslim women feminists

00:36:42.310 --> 00:36:44.520 align:middle line:90%
to tell her own stories.

00:36:44.520 --> 00:36:45.850 align:middle line:90%
I think it's so important.

00:36:45.850 --> 00:36:48.160 align:middle line:84%
I think so much that
happens in this culture,

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:49.820 align:middle line:84%
people are speaking
for other people

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:51.890 align:middle line:84%
rather than allowing people
to speak for themselves.

00:36:51.890 --> 00:36:54.220 align:middle line:84%
And one of things that we're
working on more and more

00:36:54.220 --> 00:36:56.130 align:middle line:84%
in V-Day, first of all
V-Day's owned by everybody,

00:36:56.130 --> 00:36:58.900 align:middle line:84%
so everybody's
having their voice.

00:36:58.900 --> 00:37:02.970 align:middle line:84%
But I feel like Jerin has taught
me so much about Muslim culture

00:37:02.970 --> 00:37:03.840 align:middle line:90%
that we didn't know.

00:37:03.840 --> 00:37:06.840 align:middle line:84%
And I think why aren't we
learning from each other?

00:37:06.840 --> 00:37:09.620 align:middle line:84%
We make all these assumptions
that just flat line experience

00:37:09.620 --> 00:37:12.330 align:middle line:84%
and close doors, rather
than saying, oh, talk to me.

00:37:12.330 --> 00:37:13.330 align:middle line:90%
Talk to me about your culture.

00:37:13.330 --> 00:37:15.450 align:middle line:84%
Tell me your interpretation,
or your experience

00:37:15.450 --> 00:37:16.910 align:middle line:84%
with your culture,
because everyone

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:19.230 align:middle line:84%
has such different
experiences with culture.

00:37:19.230 --> 00:37:20.880 align:middle line:84%
You know, you go to
different Muslim countries,

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:24.160 align:middle line:84%
and how the Quran is interpreted
is completely different.

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:25.670 align:middle line:84%
You go to Pakistan,
it's one thing.

00:37:25.670 --> 00:37:27.270 align:middle line:84%
You go to Bangladesh,
it's completely different.

00:37:27.270 --> 00:37:28.630 align:middle line:84%
You go to Turkey,
it's one thing.

00:37:28.630 --> 00:37:31.980 align:middle line:84%
You go to wherever, it's
completely different.

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:35.190 align:middle line:84%
And I think people's
experience in relationship

00:37:35.190 --> 00:37:38.780 align:middle line:84%
to religion colors so
much of what it is,

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:40.140 align:middle line:90%
and how it's practiced.

00:37:40.140 --> 00:37:42.810 align:middle line:84%
And yet, we make all these
assumptions here that, I think,

00:37:42.810 --> 00:37:44.700 align:middle line:84%
got brought on
very much by 9/11,

00:37:44.700 --> 00:37:48.040 align:middle line:84%
and this desire to have this
monolithic experience which

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:50.680 align:middle line:84%
froze Islamic
people in one place,

00:37:50.680 --> 00:37:54.580 align:middle line:84%
and Americans in another,
as if Muslim people

00:37:54.580 --> 00:37:55.630 align:middle line:90%
weren't Americans, you know?

00:37:55.630 --> 00:37:56.330 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:37:56.330 --> 00:37:59.154 align:middle line:84%
And I think part of it is how
do you engender conversation?

00:37:59.154 --> 00:38:01.020 align:middle line:84%
We only have a couple more
minutes here together today,

00:38:01.020 --> 00:38:02.550 align:middle line:90%
and I was curious.

00:38:02.550 --> 00:38:04.480 align:middle line:84%
So in this campaign,
this worldwide campaign

00:38:04.480 --> 00:38:08.020 align:middle line:84%
that you're imagining, and
orchestrating, and bringing

00:38:08.020 --> 00:38:11.460 align:middle line:84%
into manifestation
against sexual violence,

00:38:11.460 --> 00:38:13.270 align:middle line:84%
what do you see would be
some milestones in the next 5

00:38:13.270 --> 00:38:13.969 align:middle line:90%
or 10 years ago?

00:38:13.969 --> 00:38:16.160 align:middle line:84%
Where would you like to
see it 10 years from now,

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:19.440 align:middle line:84%
and how would you actually
get to that point?

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:21.380 align:middle line:84%
Well, I think if we look
at last year and some

00:38:21.380 --> 00:38:23.480 align:middle line:84%
of the amazing results
of One Billion Rising,

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:25.360 align:middle line:90%
we have seen laws change.

00:38:25.360 --> 00:38:29.030 align:middle line:84%
We've seen coalitions built.
And I think coalition-building--

00:38:29.030 --> 00:38:31.490 align:middle line:84%
we were talking
earlier about mind

00:38:31.490 --> 00:38:34.270 align:middle line:90%
shifts and evolutionary leaps.

00:38:34.270 --> 00:38:39.220 align:middle line:84%
I think part of what we've done
in organizing in resistance

00:38:39.220 --> 00:38:40.850 align:middle line:90%
is we've siloed things.

00:38:40.850 --> 00:38:43.190 align:middle line:84%
We put environmental
degradation over here,

00:38:43.190 --> 00:38:45.020 align:middle line:84%
and we put economic
injustice over here.

00:38:45.020 --> 00:38:47.100 align:middle line:84%
And we put Islamophobia
over here, and we put--

00:38:47.100 --> 00:38:49.210 align:middle line:90%
but in fact, there's one story.

00:38:49.210 --> 00:38:51.050 align:middle line:84%
We're all in one
story, and I think

00:38:51.050 --> 00:38:54.480 align:middle line:84%
the more we can build coalitions
where everybody's included

00:38:54.480 --> 00:38:57.050 align:middle line:84%
in the story, and everybody's
issues become integrated

00:38:57.050 --> 00:38:59.400 align:middle line:84%
and connected to
everybody else's issues,

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:01.780 align:middle line:84%
the more possibility
there is for radical,

00:39:01.780 --> 00:39:03.450 align:middle line:90%
revolutionary transformation.

00:39:03.450 --> 00:39:06.400 align:middle line:84%
And I think One Billion Rising
is doing that organically.

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:10.250 align:middle line:84%
And I don't really know how
dancing figures into it,

00:39:10.250 --> 00:39:13.300 align:middle line:84%
but there's something
about the act of dancing

00:39:13.300 --> 00:39:14.660 align:middle line:90%
that is liberatory.

00:39:14.660 --> 00:39:16.150 align:middle line:90%
It's so--

00:39:16.150 --> 00:39:18.110 align:middle line:90%
Even to Black Sabbath?

00:39:18.110 --> 00:39:19.710 align:middle line:90%
To anything.

00:39:19.710 --> 00:39:22.530 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think there is
a liberation of your body,

00:39:22.530 --> 00:39:24.600 align:middle line:84%
but there's also a
liberation of your mind.

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:26.520 align:middle line:90%
And so you get out of your silo.

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:28.270 align:middle line:90%
Your body is your silo, right?

00:39:28.270 --> 00:39:30.190 align:middle line:84%
So when you dance, you
break out of that silo,

00:39:30.190 --> 00:39:31.710 align:middle line:90%
and you begin to say, oh my god.

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:32.590 align:middle line:90%
You're dancing too.

00:39:32.590 --> 00:39:34.130 align:middle line:84%
So what's your
connection to this?

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:34.830 align:middle line:90%
And you're dancing.

00:39:34.830 --> 00:39:35.637 align:middle line:90%
You're 14.

00:39:35.637 --> 00:39:36.670 align:middle line:90%
What's your connection to this?

00:39:36.670 --> 00:39:39.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you begin to see
all these places where you're

00:39:39.220 --> 00:39:41.440 align:middle line:84%
rooted and
interconnected, and then

00:39:41.440 --> 00:39:44.830 align:middle line:84%
the movement gets enlarged,
and the energy gets enlarged.

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:48.360 align:middle line:10%
And I was just looking
at the videos of women

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:52.170 align:middle line:10%
in wheelchairs dancing, and
then cut to men just boogieing

00:39:52.170 --> 00:39:53.030 align:middle line:10%
in the middle of streets.

00:39:53.030 --> 00:39:54.963 align:middle line:84%
And then you're in the middle
of a desert, and there are--

00:39:54.963 --> 00:39:56.590 align:middle line:90%
What's the URL again for that?

00:39:56.590 --> 00:39:58.550 align:middle line:84%
-Onebillionrising.org
-Nice one.

00:39:58.550 --> 00:40:00.760 align:middle line:84%
Do you have any
last comment to add?

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:02.875 align:middle line:84%
You know, the most
important reason Islam

00:40:02.875 --> 00:40:06.490 align:middle line:84%
is feminist is because
one of the main beliefs

00:40:06.490 --> 00:40:09.540 align:middle line:84%
is you can't fight with
the oneness of God,

00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:11.780 align:middle line:84%
meaning there's
only God above you.

00:40:11.780 --> 00:40:14.690 align:middle line:84%
And if I put a man
above me, that just

00:40:14.690 --> 00:40:16.912 align:middle line:90%
breaks down Islam completely.

00:40:16.912 --> 00:40:17.890 align:middle line:90%
Right on.

00:40:17.890 --> 00:40:18.650 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much.

00:40:18.650 --> 00:40:19.630 align:middle line:84%
So beautiful to
talk to both of you.

00:40:19.630 --> 00:40:20.830 align:middle line:84%
I really appreciate it.
-Yeah, thank you.

